{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "I argue, contrary to much of the literature, that Ockham believes that if one were given this command, one would be obligated to refrain from loving God and would also be able to fulfill this obligation without any moral wrongdoing.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Among other results, this study will help clarify Ockham's much-discussed claim that loving God is 'a necessarily virtuous act.'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Yet despite the expansive literature on this brief question, there is no clear consensus on what Ockham's answer is to the issues raised in it.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Some think that Ockham's considered view is that the command in question cannot be obeyed, others that the command cannot be disobeyed.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "I intend to show in the remainder of this paper that in Quodlibet III.14 Ockham affirms the following five claims:",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "1. The Contingency of Moral Status: No act of a creaturely will is necessarily virtuous, strictly speaking.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "2. Loving God Above All is Actually Always Virtuous: As a matter of fact, given God's actual commands, whenever any creature elicits an act of loving God above all else, that act is virtuous.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "3. Possible to be Commanded to Not Love God: God can, in the actual world, consistent with his actual commands, also command some individual to not elicit an act of loving God at some time t.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "4. Impossible to Disobey a Divine Command to Not Love God: If God commands an individual to not elicit an act of loving God at some time t, it is impossible for that individual to disobey that command by eliciting an act of loving God above all else at t (though it is possible for the individual to disobey the command by eliciting a lesser kind of love).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "5. Possible to Obey a Divine Command to Not Love God: If God commands an individual to not elicit an act of loving God at some time t, it is possible for that individual to obey the command by not eliciting an act of loving God at t.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Ockham affirms (or at least sees no reason to doubt) that God can give Brennan this command, and so holds claim #3, that it is Possible to be Commanded to Not Love God.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Ockham concludes claim #4, that it is Impossible to Disobey a Divine Command to Not Love God.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "I suggest we have good reason to think Ockham endorses claim #5, that it is Possible to Obey a Divine Command to Not Love God.",
      "label": "premise"
    }
  },
